Introduction
In this article, we explore why the operator+= in C++ can accept brace-enclosed initializer lists while operator+ cannot. Understanding this issue is crucial for C++ developers, especially when dealing with operator overloading in modern C++.
The Issue Explained
When working with C++11 and later, initializer lists are a powerful feature that allows for more natural syntax when initializing collections. However, when you try to use these lists with overloaded operators, things don't always go as expected.
